This award supported the creation of a week-long field course in Atmospheric Chemistry for undergraduate Environmental Science majors at the Storm Peak Laboratory (SPL) in Steamboat Springs, CO during March 2023. The course was leveraged by a prior research collaboration between the project investigators, Drs. Lynne Gratz and A. Gannet Hallar, that involved continuous atmospheric measurements of trace gases, aerosols, meteorology, and mercury at SPL. The student field experience was part of a regular 3.5-week course block at Colorado College, a primarily undergraduate institution in Colorado Springs, CO. The course learning goals were for students to:

 connect course concepts to the natural world and to practical research questions;
gain field experience outside the classroom and in a world class research facility;
develop data analysis methods to address a specific research question;
engage in the collaborative research process, with classmates and professional scientists;
present results, orally and in writing, to enhance scientific communication skills.





Students spent the first two weeks of the course on campus learning fundamental concepts in tropospheric and stratospheric chemistry, while also engaging with primary literature from SPL and other mountaintop atmospheric observatories. They also carried out laboratory assignments designed to build analytical skills, such as air mass transport modeling and graphical or statistical methods, that would later underpin their final course projects. While at SPL, students learned about laboratory operations, instrumental methods, and sampling design while also making measurements of the local atmosphere. Students then devised final research projects centered on the quality-assured data generated from the co-PIs aforementioned collaborative research project, which they summarized in oral in-class presentations (with co-PI Hallar in virtual attendance) and written extended abstracts to complete the course. Throughout the course, careful efforts were taken to ensure an inclusive, safe, engaging, and impactful learning experience for all participants. This field experience demonstrated a unique opportunity to broaden the undergraduate learning experience through the application of course concepts at an internationally-renowned atmospheric research station in collaboration with scholars from research-oriented institutions.					Last Modified: 06/19/2024

